<br>
In regards to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:blue;">River / Wade</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> only I use a few ground rules with my fly lines. I don't have enough room on this website to talk about fly lines used in conjunction with lake fishing or fishing from a boat. We could talk about the significance of that for days.<br>
<br>
Sink tip lines work very well when fishing a structure, a specific depth, or a specific rate of return strip. The White and Norfork rivers have many ledges, pockets and such. A sink tip line does a good job of allowing you to trace the edges of that structure with a nymph or streamer. If you are fishing a deep pocket and want to allow the fly to fall off the edge then rise up the side you are standing on a sink tip is perfect. There is a hole on the Little Red that I'll fish a crayfish pattern with. I'll cast to the far side of the pool and crawl it off the far side. I'll swim it across the bottom, then fast strip it up the near bank. <br>
<br>
For a ledge I'll usually stand directly across from it. I'll cast a sink tip slightly upstream and allow it to sink and trace the edge of the ledge. Generally the surface currents around a ledge are too uneven to fish with a floating line and still get a natural drift.<br>
<br>
If you are fishing a nymph or an emerger a sink tip can keep it at a constant level in the water column. If your fly is neutrally buoyant it will suspend at the depth of the sink tip. Many people fish this style exclusively and claim it is a very successfull technique. As yet I don't have it mastered.<br>
<br>
For streamers like wooly buggers I more often than not use a sink tip. The rate of strip is usually determined by the depth of the water and the length of the tip. I try to keep a streamer within close proximity to the bottom. I think you'll find you will get considerably more hook-ups with a sink tip than you will a floating line.<br>
<br>
I use deep sinking lines for fishing deep pools and fast water. Anywhere that you are concerned about surface current, you should use a full sinking line in lieu of a sink tip. For instance there is a pool on the Norfork that I often fish. It has a fast run at the top that falls off into a deep pool almost immediately. If I am fishing a sculpin pattern I'll fish a full sinking line. The line hits the water and sinks out of the current almost immediately. I change lines depending on how often I hang in the rocks below. This allows the sculpin to get into the rocks and not drift according to the surface current. I can slowly roll my fly along the bottom and let it swing fully across the pool. In a pool that is 8 feet deep or more you would want to use a full sinking line almost exclusively.<br>
<br>
I hope that at least &quot;touches&quot; the high spots. You could easily write a book on fishing different lines with different structures and different patterns. The possibilities are endless. The best advise I could give you is to visualize the structure you have and how you want the fly to track. What are the obstacles in your way. Just as a for instance if you are bass fishing out of a boat you can use a long sink tip to trace the ever deepening bank line. Throwing along the shore and pulling your fly into deeper water. Just imagine what you want your fly to do.<br>
<br>
Don't get stuck with using floating fly lines only. You will be very restricted in the areas you can fish. Next we'll talk about single hand spey casting and what water that will open up to you.<br>
<br>
